lg.l:
In fear, utter voices of thunder; the
                        woods of France embosom the sound;

                            Bentley (*Writings* volume 2, page 801) and Erdman (286) read "In fear," as "In fear."

Written in my bosom. Neckar rise, leave
                        the kingdom, thy life is surrounded with snares;

                            Bentley (*Writings* volume 2, page 807) and Erdman (291) read "Neckar" as "Necker."

His benevolent hand, looking on the
                        Archbishop, who changed as pale as lead;

                            Bentley reads "who changed as pale as lead;" as "who, changed as pale as lead," (*Writings* volume 2 page 811).

The pale fires of Aumont into the
                        chamber, as a father that bows to his son;

                            Bentley reads "bows to his son;" as "bows to his son," (*Writings* volume 2 page 812).
